Local Engagement as a Counter to Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble each other everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of once dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened by the populist tide to launch a counteroffensive.
Yet neither denial nor complacency will resolve the stalled political situation.
The Progressives must regroup, and that begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are alone in the forest, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has gone off track.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and government policy has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, for example, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy cities benefiting from globalization and the rest of the country.
Yet before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national prime minister had implemented tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters rather than only through the filters of media and opinion polls.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What voters told the interviewers then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct towards women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of his opponents' jokes; however, the laughter of his opponents quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer for the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to vote, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
Voters want to be treated as political actors in their own right and not as pawns in someone else's chess game.
Moreover, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions from national governments alone.
These challenges demand profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Whoever can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well does not need a party apparatus that is centuries old.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
With La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from reading courses after school and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems in order to strengthen communities in this way.
Such projects should today be seen as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding pathways for political and community engagement will be essential to its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policies daily "live," parties have already laid the groundwork for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what you have to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the harsh lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Reestablishing the connection to voters' concerns therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
